What LAMP Stack Means

The LAMP stack is a widely used open-source software stack for building, hosting, and running dynamic web applications. The acronym “LAMP” stands for:

L – Linux: the operating system that provides the foundation for the stack.

A – Apache: the web server software that handles HTTP requests and serves web pages.

M – MySQL: a relational database management system used to store and manage data.

P – PHP: a server-side scripting language used to generate dynamic content.

Each component works together to deliver dynamic web content: Apache receives requests from a user’s browser, PHP processes server-side logic, MySQL stores and retrieves data, and Linux underpins the entire environment.

Although PHP is the most common scripting language in LAMP, Perl or Python can also be used in its place.

Why LAMP Is Popular

It’s entirely open-source and free, lowering development costs.

It provides a stable and flexible platform well-suited for web development.

Many popular web applications (like WordPress and Drupal) use the LAMP stack.